HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 720
By Moon
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Eugene John Burke.
WHEREAS, we were greatly saddened to learn of the passing of Eugene John Burke of
Seymour; and
WHEREAS, Eugene Burke, born on April 6, 1936, in New York, New York, lived a life
marked by kindness, dedication to family, and a willingness to serve others; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Burke worked as an educator in the automotive industry for over thirty
years, sharing his knowledge and shaping countless careers; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Burke became a Freemason in the late 1980s while living in Grand
Blanc, Michigan; he served as Master of the Charles Durant Lodge in 1997 and Master of the
New Providence Lodge in Maryville in 2025; and
WHEREAS, he also was a presiding officer of the Maryville York Rite Bodies and
achieved membership in the Knights of the York Cross of Honor Tennessee Priory; and
WHEREAS, Eugene Burke's favorite pastimes were spending time with his family and
friends and working on home improvement projects; and
WHEREAS, deeply devoted to his family, Mr. Burke enjoyed the loving companionship
of his wife, June, and was the proud father of two daughters, Dawn Burke Colvin and Deborah
Burke; and
WHEREAS, he will be sadly mourned but fondly remembered by his wife and children
and a host of family and friends; and
WHEREAS, Eugene Burke was preceded in death by his brother, Raymond James
Burke, Sr.; and
HJR0720
010641
- 1 -

WHEREAS, Mr. Burke leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in public
life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should remember the bountiful life of this exceptional
public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Eugene John Burke, reflecting fondly upon his
impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage and
conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Burke.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
